title.narrative: WASH IN INSTITUTIONS

description.narrative: Education and health systems in selected districts have enhanced capacity and provide sustainable, inclusive Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH) services in schools andhealth facilities., which contributes to Safe And Equitable Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Services And Practices, Safe And Equitable Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Services And Practices (Covid), Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Systems And Empowerment Of Communities. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Vulnerable groups have increased access to safe and affordable water supply, sanitation, and hygiene

title.narrative: Education and health systems in selected districts have enhanced capacity and provide sustainable, inclusive WASH services inschools andhealth facilities.

description.narrative: Despite the COVID-19 pandemic undermining the performance of the education and health systems, in 2021, UNICEF worked with government and partners to strengthen government system’s resilience to ensure the continuity and delivery of essential WASH, education, and health services. UNICEF improved WASH infrastructure in 104 schools and 32 healthcare facilities reaching an estimated 121,145 schoolchildren and 185,000 patients. The government with UNICEF prepared a national costed plan and investment case for WASH in schools and equipped over 900 practitioners in WASH, education and health with pertinent knowledge and tools to plan, implement, and monitor sustainable WASH services in institutions.; | Status:On-track | As-of Date:13/12/2021
